commentBody:
@Cat Lady Margaret 

We could dress alike, but then I would just be a CARBON COPY.



Do emus wear clothes or just hair shirts?

@Lewis

What about 26D?
I loved the clue once I got it, brought a smile to my face

@Rich in Atlanta 

Ah, I didn't think to search for the plural. Thanks.

The singular form could go into a 16 x 14 grid or else a Sunday grid (of course).

@Mike 

And yet you won't protest GOLD when it should be GOLDEN?
(And if it didn't 'work' then don't use it, dear Constructor!)

@john ezra 

There’s wisdom in the book that goes beyond writing style.  I have always tried to live by the Strunkian advice, quoted by White at the end of his introduction, “If you don’t know how to pronounce a word, say it loud!”  

If you don’t mind embarrassing yourself, you can learn a lot. Or as E.B. said, “why compound ignorance with inaudibility?”

@Marshall Walthew 

I earned some nice money editing dissertations for doctoral students who had been told by their advisors to "find someone who can help you."  Smart people making original contributions to knowledge, but just Not Good Writers.  

It was interesting on several levels...

@Andrzej

You’re on the right wavelength for the theme. MASKS were definitely a part of a style back during the pandemic, when people color-coordinated them to their outfits. 

Although going out on the street wearing a MASK, an APRON, a single GLOVE (a la Michael Jackson?), and a HAT might get you some attention.

@Kris T 

Right, thanks. I bought a playfully colorful mask myself back then (but I did not wear it in the end since it did not meet medical standards) but I suppose I forgot all about it as a form denial that those horrible few years ever happened.

It appears I am not open-minded enough - when thinking in English - to fully grasp NYT puzzle themes. Even when I do in fact get them, I do not trust myself. "Surely this can't be it?!"

@Vaer 

Not only do I remember EGG CREAMS, I made them behind the counter at my 👴🏾 pharmacy in Sheepshead Bay. 

There was also a vanilla egg cream for those who didn’t care for chocolate.

@Anne 

That sort of repetition and echoing of clues and answers day to day is quite common. It is a wink to the regular readers, lagniappe, like frequent solver points. It helps you remember the answers and gets you used to the NYT puzzle style.

Appreciate it as a friendly hello.

@CaptainQuahog - Ugh. I hate autocorrect, and I have no idea why it "corrected" Strunk to Strink. 
Or maybe it was just a typo on my part. 

Which raises the universal question: Orange you grapefruit for spelt Czech?

@John 
Tin-type




Emus are made of polyester

@Rich in Atlanta 

that is one heckuva puzzle with all those initials.

I hadn't yet checked the news today, so went to the AJC.  I assume you're referring to the death of MLKjr's youngest son from prostate cancer. Sad that prostate cancer is just one more health problem that hits harder at the African-American population.

@Bill - you remind me of two things: the “Buffy” Double-Meat Palace episode where Riley reappears and she asks, dismayed, “you can smell that?”
and
how my memory was triggered when I saw that episode, for the days in grad school when my partner was a chef in a fine restaurant. There was nothing to be done about it, the residual kitchen smell was just a part of our life…

@Marlene 
If it is your only comment in this specific forum, you will have no need to bribe the emus with treats.  ;)

........................................................

@Bill 
My friend's dad had an album called, "Everything You Always Wanted to Hear on the Moog (But Were Afraid to Ask For.)" The joke on the cover was that it was 'semi-conducted' by Andrew Kazdin and Thomas Shepard. I think my favorite piece was Ravel's Bolero

We had a small-ish Moog console in our high school band room, and we played around with it a bit, but the only time it ever got serious use was for the cannons in the 1812 Overture.

@Linda Jo 
Well, this subject has certainly come up plenty of times before in this column, but your use of the term “XYL” I think may be a debut. It went right over my head, but perhaps some of the reccos got it. It didn’t take much to track it down, however. We don’t hear much these days about Ham radio hobbyists, but it was a big thing for awhile. For an interesting take on the whole XYL thing, check out:

<a href="http://tinyurl.com/ycxf2398" target="_blank">http://tinyurl.com/ycxf2398</a>

@Hardroch 

Yes, XYL is anachronistic and chauvinistic slang. I don't take as seriously as that article, but it is a bit ham-fisted.

I wondered how many readers would recognize it!

@Barry Ancona - Yes, corn. Much better. 

But, you do know that corn plants have feelings, too, right? They even have children -- there was a movie made about that. 

BTW, I am surprised that so many people were flummoxed by GDAŃSK, considering the history of Lech Wałęsa and Solidarność. It was big big news back in the day!

@Bruce Do kids get asked to memorize poems any more? My grandfather, who wrote a few of his own, encouraged me to. He said the ones you learned early in life would stick when others didn't and he was so right.  I cannot  memorize Larkin's "Church Going"  no  matter how  hard I try. Or all of De La Mere's "Farewell".
 Actually I'm in awe of your 7th grade self. Our 8th grade teacher made us each memorize  a Poe poem and I tried for "The Bells" (no  "Annabelle Lee" for me)  but couldn't do it. I may have  managed "The  Raven. "
  But I can do Hopkins' "Pied Beauty"--my mother's favorite.

@Sam Lyons 
Yeah, I went down the same rabbit hole (just like I did when guard donkeys came up the other day). Sounds like a traditional approach has been to use gelding llamas for guards, but it has more recently been suggested that it may  actually be safer for all concerned to use female llamas. For anyone curious, with a couple of minutes to spare, an interesting discussion is at:

<a href="http://tinyurl.com/397sc7kz" target="_blank">http://tinyurl.com/397sc7kz</a>

@Daniel 

The ELKS Club is a community service club that exists through the US. 

For them, the plural of ELK is indeed ELKS.
